This graph structure is designed to encode the syntactic and
semantic relationships inherent in Modelica code, enabling more
effective retrieval of relevant knowledge during code generation.
To further illustrate the dependency relationships in Modelica
modeling, as well as the nodes, attributes, and edges constructed

Trovato et al.
in our property graph, we present a simple case in Listing 2. This
example serves as a test case for "RealType.Great" from the In-
dustrialControlSystems library, designed to perform real-number
comparisons. To simulate this case, three components must be
instantiated, which is shown in lines 2-3. These components are
instantiated and connected through the connect statements, estab-
lishing dependency relationships that enable real-time comparison
of sine and cosine signal sizes.
To systematically represent these dependencies, we construct
a property graph for this case, where components, signals, and
parameters are modeled as nodes, and their interactions as edges,
as shown in Figure 4. By structuring the Modelica code in this
manner, the property graph provides a structured representation
that facilitates dependency resolution.
To construct the property graph, we define a set of node types,
including connectors, equations, parameters, and interfaces, as well
as edge types, such as extension, connection, and invocation, to rep-
resent the intricate interconnections within a Modelica code.These
nodes and edges are systematically structured to capture Modelica’s
hierarchical and modular nature, ensuring that the constructed
property graph effectively represents the correlations between
Modelica objects and their functional dependencies. We utilize
the component-related information from 𝐷𝑎𝑡𝑎𝑠𝑒𝑡𝑠 𝑓 𝑡 as the refer-
ence corpus to construct a Property Graph Index. This corpus
comprises a diverse collection of technical documents from various
Modelica libraries, along with detailed descriptions and underlying
principles of components.
1  model  Test_RealGreat
2  IndustrialControlSystems.Logical.Comparisons.RealType
.Great  great(Ts=0.001,eps=0.01);
3  Modelica.Blocks.Sources.Sine  sine(f=1, amplitude=1);
4  Modelica.Blocks.Sources.Cosine  cosine(f=1, amplitude=
1, phase=1.57);
5  Boolean y;
6  equation
7  connect(great.u1, sine.y) ;
8  connect(great.u2, cosine.y) ;
9  y=great.y;
10  end  Test_RealGreat;
Listing 2: A Case to Illustrate Dependency Relationship.
Test_RealGreat {type: "Model", category: "TestCase"}
├── [INSTANTIATES] → great {type: "IndustrialControlSystems....Great"}
│     ├── [HAS_INPUT] → great.u1 {type: "Real"}
│     ├── [HAS_INPUT] → great.u2 {type: "Real"}
│     ├── [HAS_OUTPUT] → great.y {type: "Boolean"}
├── [INSTANTIATES] → sine {type: "Modelica.Blocks.Sources.Sine"}
│     ├── [HAS_OUTPUT] → sine.y {type: "Real"}
│     ├── [HAS_PARAMETER] → {f, amplitude, phase, ...} {type: "Real"}
├── [INSTANTIATES] → cosine {type: "Modelica.Blocks.Sources.Cosine"}
│     ├── [HAS_OUTPUT] → cosine.y {type: "Real"}
│     ├── [HAS_PARAMETER] → {f, amplitude, phase, ...} {type: "Real"}
├── [CONNECTED_TO {mode: "continuous"}] → great.u1 ↔ sine.y
├── [CONNECTED_TO {mode: "continuous"}] → great.u2 ↔ cosine.y
├── [HAS_PARAMETER] → y {type: "Boolean"}
├── [ASSIGNS {depends_on: ["great.u1", "great.u2"]}] → y ← great.y
Figure 4: Property Graph Representation of Test_RealGreat
Model.
